PanelContainer

PanelContainer and MarginContainer maximize Control nodes

PanelContainer provides a background for child Control nodes. MarginContainer provides padding around the edges.

Both nodes are very similar in that they maximize their Control children’s sizes, making them useful as root nodes for UI scenes.

In this guide, you will learn:

  • The differences between PanelContainer and MarginContainer.
  • The benefits of MarginContainer as a root scene.
  • How to create a drag and drop inventory.
  • How to build trading cards out of Control nodes.

PanelContainer and MarginContainer’s key features

All the following key features and use cases apply to both nodes. We primarily use PanelContainer because it’s easier to see its placement in these scenes.

Maximize Control children

A Container node handles the position and size of its Control children automatically. Add a child to a PanelContainer, and it automatically expands to fit the PanelContainer’s size.

If you want to split the PanelContainer for other children to use, add a VBoxContainer or HBoxContainer, and place your control children in those nodes. You can read more in the HBoxContainer guide.

This is true for the MarginContainer as well, except it’s transparent, and Custom Constants -> Margin adjusts its margins.

Put Control children on the edges and corners

Although the general purpose of a PanelContainer is to expand its children, you can position a child on the edges and corners of a PanelContainer by adjusting the child’s Size Flags.

You can learn more about size flags by reading the HBoxContainer guide.

You can’t use the Expand size flag on children of a PanelContainer because all children extend their bounding box to fit up all the available space. Fill, Shrink End, and Shrink Center change the size and positions of the node accordingly.

Although the Anchor properties in all Control nodes do something similar, Anchors do not work inside containers. They are better suited for loose Control nodes.

Change appearance using StyleBoxes

You can change the appearance of a PanelContainer by editing the Custom Styles -> Panel property. Here are some options to choose from when styling a PanelContainer:

  • StyleBoxEmpty makes the PanelContainer transparent. This makes it look like a default MarginContainer.
  • StyleBoxFlat creates a colored background and border. You can adjust the border’s thickness, give its corners rounded edges, and add a shadow to the style box.
  • StyleBoxTexture lets you style your PanelContainer with a nine-patch texture.
  • StyleBoxLine creates a thin line that scales in one direction. The HSeparator and VSeparator nodes use this resource.

Report when the children have changed

The sort_children signal emits when a child is added or removed to the PanelContainer.

Normally, a PanelContainer grows to fit any growing Control children. However, the PanelContainer won’t shrink to fit a shrinking child node. We can shrink the PanelContainer back to fit the new child size using the sort_children signal because it emits when the child changes its size. We’ll see this in action when we cover dynamic speech bubbles that fit dialogue.

How to use a PanelContainer and MarginContainer in practice

Here are some real-world use cases for PanelContainer and MarginContainer.

Fit a dynamic speech bubble to dialogue

Some games with dialogue choose to present dialogue as a speech bubble which fits the length of the text. Games like Oxenfree and Night in the Woods use this effect.

Game: Night in the Woods (2017)

You can achieve this using a PanelContainer with a Label child.

Here is the way we set this speech bubble up:

In our implementation, we used a CenterContainer to center the bubble on the screen. You can move the CenterContainer to move the speech bubble elsewhere.

To set the speech bubble up, we need some dialogue.

extends Node2D

## Display speed of the text in characters per second.
const TEXT_DISPLAY_SPEED := 50.0
const LINES = [
    "What does all this do? I don't trust it,\ndon't touch anything.",
    "I found it! There's something under here!",
    "Ugh...\nso bored...help me...",
    "Thanks for the help!",
    "You go on ahead, I'll hang back in case the others show up.",
    "Wait...\nAre you really sure about that?",
]

onready var _label: Label = $CenterContainer/PanelContainer/Label
onready var _tween: Tween = $Tween

Now, we need a function to animate the Label’s Percent Visible property. The Label’s size won’t change, but the text will show itself gradually as we increase Percent Visible.

We use a Tween to adjust Percent Visible because it gives us more control over how fast the text appears.

The Tween duration is len(_label.text) / TEXT_DISPLAY_SPEED. In this equation, we make the duration of the animation proportional to the number of characters. Each character in the Label should appear at regular intervals. We can then speed up or slow down the animation by altering the text display speed constant.

func _play_dialog() -> void:
    _label.text = LINES.front()
    # We cycle lines of text in the array.
    LINES.push_back(LINES.pop_front())
    _tween.interpolate_property(
        _label, "percent_visible", 0.0, 1.0, len(_label.text) / TEXT_DISPLAY_SPEED
    )
    _tween.start()

We could instead reveal text by animating the Visible Characters property every frame, but this risks making the dialogue framerate dependent without more code.

Lastly, we tie this input to the player’s “interact” action.

func _unhandled_input(event: InputEvent) -> void:
    if event.is_action_pressed("interact"):
        _play_dialog()

If you don’t want the bubble always to be in the center, you can remove the CenterContainer. Without it, the dialogue grows outwards to the left. The Grow Direction property of the PanelContainer controls this growth as it gets new text.

Grow Direction -> Begin makes the dialogue bubble expand to the right.

Grow Direction -> End makes the dialogue bubble expand to the left.

Grow Direction -> Both makes the dialogue bubble expand in the middle.

We used CenterContainer to make it clear that the dialogue bubble should remain centered, but using the Grow Direction -> Both setting works the same in this case. We’d recommend using CenterContainer if you want to move the speech bubble but still keep it centered to a specific area.

Draw a border and shadow around a card

When creating a card game in Godot, you may want to draw an outline around a Control node or adding a drop shadow to it.

A PanelContainer shines in this regard because it’s easier to use than MarginContainer.

Shadows can add a lot of depth to your user interfaces, especially when multiple elements are moving around.

In this situation, PanelContainer is useful because it fits around its child Control nodes and can draw a StyleBox behind them with this outline and drop shadow.

We can create cards for a card game using a PanelContainer to draw the border around the card and the drop shadow indicating its height.

The card has a PanelContainer for the background with a VBoxContainer to sort its contents.

For the PanelContainer, we can add a new StyleBox with Border Width, Border Color, Corner Radius for rounding the corners, and a Shadow.

If the contents of our card increase or decrease in size, our PanelContainer automatically surrounds it with our nicely styled border and shadow. Because of the margin of our PanelContainer, the contents can’t overlap the border at all.

A fantastic resource to learn more about using shadows in user interface design is Google’s material design documentation.

Hold icons in a drag and drop inventory

A drag and drop inventory is a common feature in games like Minecraft and Diablo.

Game: Minecraft (2011)

Although it takes multiple nodes to create, a PanelContainer’s role is to provide a background and expand the items in the inventory.

Our goal is to make an inventory that can move items between slots and swap items between slots.

Godot has three useful methods to drag and drop data between Control nodes: get_drag_data(), can_drop_data() and drop_data(). Here’s what calls these methods:

  • Clicking and holding on a node calls get_drag_data().
  • Dragging your mouse over another node calls can_drop_data().
  • Releasing your mouse over another node calls drop_data().

These methods must be overwritten as functions in a script to enable the drag and drop functionality. get_drag_data() should return a value (like a texture or a String) for the target node to receive. can_drop_data() should return true or false to determine if the target node is valid or not.

There’s a problem with these methods, though. Their behavior works fine for moving data, but it’s not naturally equipped to swap data. Any attempts to swap data only overwrites the dropped slot’s data. You can see this limitation in the official Godot demo for drag and drop.

We use drag forwarding to solve this.

When a Control node has drag forwarding enabled, it calls the drag and drop functions of a target node instead of its own.

This way, we only need a single parent script. All inventory slots can have set_drag_forwarding(self) called on them from our parent script, which sends their method calls to our one script.

Drag forwarding is necessary because it reports the involved Control nodes in every method call. It’s like reporting physics bodies in an Area2D using body_entered. This lets us swap data to the last Control node we dragged if we end up overwriting existing data.

Here’s the setup for our scene:

A PanelContainer called RecoveryPanel is the parent of our GridContainer with PanelContainer slots. This is one way to preserve data that is accidentally dropped outside of a valid drop target. By default, we lose data dropped outside of a valid drop target, so this panel catches it and returns it to the parent script using a signal.

extends Control

# We store a reference to the previously dragged item when swapping it with
# another.
var _last_dragged_item: TextureRect

onready var _grid: GridContainer = $RecoveryPanel/GridContainer
onready var _recovery_panel: PanelContainer = $RecoveryPanel


func _ready() -> void:
    # First, we find all the draggable items in the inventory.
    var texture_rects := []
    for item_slot in _grid.get_children():
        for item in item_slot.get_children():
            if item is TextureRect:
                texture_rects.append(item)

    # We then redirect calls from the children's drag and drop functions to this
    # script.
    for item in texture_rects:
        item.set_drag_forwarding(self)

    # We use a panel in the background to detect when the player drags an item
    # away from the inventory slots.
    _recovery_panel.connect(
        "data_recovered", self, "_on_RecoveryPanel_data_recovered"
    )

Before getting into the drag and drop method calls, we need to see what we’re dragging. We can make a function that creates a TextureRect using a texture. We’ll later use this function to send a TextureRect to the built-in set_drag_preview() function, which attaches an image of the data to our mouse cursor.

# Creates a smaller preview image to display when calling set_drag_preview()
func make_preview(texture: Texture) -> TextureRect:
    var preview := TextureRect.new()
    preview.rect_size = Vector2(64, 64)
    preview.texture = texture
    preview.expand = true
    preview.stretch_mode = TextureRect.STRETCH_KEEP_ASPECT
    return preview

Now that everything’s set up, let’s write our drag and drop methods.

drag_data_fw() gets the texture of the Control node we dragged from and makes a preview of it. This texture is also returned so Godot can give it to the node accessed in drop_data_fw().

Our _last_dragged_item variable is the Control node we just clicked. This is important to know which slot should get an item back if we swap items or drop our data outside a valid slot by accident.

func get_drag_data_fw(_position: Vector2, source_control: Control) -> Texture:
    _last_dragged_item = source_control

    var _texture: Texture = source_control.texture
    source_control.texture = null
    set_drag_preview(make_preview(_texture))
    # We return the texture so it'll become the `dragged_texture` in
    # can_drop_data_fw() and drop_data_fw().
    return _texture

Next, we need to see if there is any data to drop. If what we grabbed was null, from an empty slot, then we don’t want to replace any textures with it.

func can_drop_data_fw(
    _position: Vector2, dragged_texture: Texture, _target_control: Control
) -> bool:
    # We check that dragged data exists to prevent us from overwriting a slot with null.
    return dragged_texture != null

We now need two pieces of functionality in our drop function: the ability to drop textures onto a slot with null data, and the ability to swap two textures.

func drop_data_fw(_position: Vector2, dragged_texture: Texture, new_slot: Control) -> void:
    var new_texture: Texture = new_slot.texture
    # If the target slot is empty, we assign the dragged texture to it.
    if new_texture == null:
        new_slot.texture = dragged_texture
    # If the target slot contains something, 
    else:
        var data_to_replace: Texture = new_slot.texture
        _last_dragged_item.texture = data_to_replace
        new_slot.texture = dragged_texture

Last for this script is to create a callback function for another script on the RecoveryPanel. This panel retrieves any data dropped outside of a slot. We can retrieve the reference to the last Control node data we grabbed and give it back to the Control node.

func _on_RecoveryPanel_data_recovered(data: Texture) -> void:
    # Any data dropped on the panel behind the grid is returned here, and set as
    # the last dragged item's texture.
    _last_dragged_item.texture = data

With our DragDropInventory script done, the last step is to create another script on the PanelContainer sitting behind the inventory. This node accepts any data that was accidentally dropped outside of the inventory slots.

It first needs a signal to send back to the inventory, which we declare with an argument that contains the dropped texture.

extends PanelContainer

signal data_recovered(texture)

We use the regular can_drop_data() and drop_data() functions since this isn’t forwarding all slots to one script. This is its own script that uses a regular signal to send data.

func can_drop_data(_position: Vector2, dragged_texture: Texture) -> bool:
    return dragged_texture != null


func drop_data(_position: Vector2, dragged_texture: Texture) -> void:
    emit_signal("data_recovered", dragged_texture)

When you have Control nodes of multiple sizes, a PanelContainer is a great way to make sure they grow to make use of the space they’re given.

The end result is a flexible system that uses native drag and drop functions found in all Control nodes.

Fit children when resizing the window

A common issue with user interfaces in Godot is making them fit the game window while resizing.

With Godot’s many tools and options for UI positioning and scaling, it can be difficult to ensure all Control nodes stay on-screen no matter the resolution.

One way to address this is to use a MarginContainer as your scene root. You can set its Anchor preset to Full Rect, so Control children fill your entire screen space. The HBoxContainer and VBoxContainer nodes can serve as dividers to automatically position and scale other Control nodes.

You can do this with a PanelContainer as well, although the StyleBox your PanelContainer is using may cover the screen.

MarginContainer is ideal for fitting UI over the game world and displaying a HUD. It’s transparent and doesn’t obstruct vision. The Custom Constants -> Margin properties let you add space between the edge of the screen and the UI. Using margins is a way to give your UI more breathing room.

For UI systems that aim for a decoupled, instanced scene approach, PanelContainer makes for a great scene root. If you prefer the background to be partially transparent, you can adjust the StyleBox or the UI Theme to let you see more information behind the UI.

Your questions

How do I change the background on a PanelContainer?

You can change the appearance of a PanelContainer by editing the Custom Styles -> Panel property.

You can also create a Theme resource, add PanelContainer class items, and change the default for the Theme there.

How do I add or remove margins on a PanelContainer?

When adjusting the StyleBox, the Content Margin property represents the number of pixels between the edge of the PanelContainer, and the Control children. These are -1 by default to maximize the space they have.

A faster way to adjust margins is to opt for a MarginContainer instead and adjust its Custom Constants to adjust margins. This avoids having to edit with StyleBox or Theme resources.

How do I move child nodes inside a PanelContainer?

PanelContainer maximizes its children by default. To move or resize control nodes inside the PanelContainer (or any container), you have a few options:

  • Use a Panel instead to move children freely.
  • Move children inside a PanelContainer by enabling the Shrink Center or Shrink End size flags.
  • Add a new container node to break up the PanelContainer.

VBoxContainer, HBoxContainer, and GridContainer are all great nodes to break up the PanelContainer space. You can also try other container nodes and see how they respond to Control children.

What are the differences between Panel, MarginContainer, and PanelContainer?

Assuming that the end goal is to hold other Control children, here are some pros and cons of using each of these nodes:

PanelContainer

Pros:

  • PanelContainer won’t shrink past its children.
  • Has a customizable background panel.
  • Maximizes children.

Cons:

  • Can prevent the parent container from fitting onto the screen.
  • Children can overlap each other.
  • Position of children can’t be reliably animated.

MarginContainer

Pros:

  • No border around children unless using custom constants.
  • Invisible background.
  • Maximizes children.

Cons:

  • No way to color it without adding a Panel or ColorRect as a child.
  • Children can overlap each other.
  • Position of children can’t be reliably animated.

Panel

Pros:

  • Completely free movement of children inside the panel.
  • Allows use of Anchors. This is a matter of personal preference.

Cons:

  • Panel can break free of children, letting them hang outside the panel.
  • Doesn’t use Size Flags. This is a matter of personal preference.
